<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>Recall 05501-R2 - FRONT DRIVE SHAFT on 4800 4x4's with FABCO TC-200 TRANSFER CASES built 6/30/1999 thru
        5/8/2002
    </stitle>
    <recall id="rec05501">
        <recallnumber>05501-R2</recallnumber>
        <market>U.S., Export</market>
        <recalldate>May, 2005</recalldate>
        <subjectfile>TRANSMISSION</subjectfile>
        <subject>FRONT DRIVE SHAFT on 4800 4x4's with FABCO TC-200 TRANSFER CASES built 6/30/1999 thru 5/8/2002
        </subject>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <vendorgroup/>

                <vendor>Fabco</vendor>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>4800
                    <daterange>
                        <startdate>06/30/1999</startdate>
                        <enddate>05/08/2002</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
                <ucodegroup/>

                <ucode>13TJZ</ucode>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <defect>
            <para>
                <emph type="boldundersc">REVISION DESCRIPTION</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="boldital">THIS IS AN ISIS ONLY NOTIFICATION. There will be NO paper mailing for this
                    revision.
                </emph>
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>There may be a burr on the drive shaft flange that can prevent it from properly mating to its
                        companion flange.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">PLEASE REVIEW THE ADDITION TO THE SERVICE PROCEDURE FOR INSTRUCTIONS.</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="boldital">SERVICE PROCEDURE</emph>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Addition of
                        <emph type="bold">NEW SHAFT DATE CODE INSPECTION</emph>.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <emph type="boldundersc">DEFECT DESCRIPTION</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="boldital">This Recall is the final remedy and supercedes Safety Recall G-03516</emph>
            </para>
            <para>
                <exhotlnk document="../recalls/Rec05501.pdf" bookname="RECALL">Print ready (PDF file) copy of the dealer
                    letter
                </exhotlnk>
            </para>
            <para>
                <exhotlnk document="../recalls/Cus05501.pdf" bookname="RECALL">Print ready (PDF file) copy of the
                    customer letter
                </exhotlnk>
            </para>
            <para>An excessive front driveshaft angle may cause accelerated wear and failure of the driveshaft and
                related components. The front driveshaft can possibly become separated from the vehicle without warning
                and get into the path of other vehicles on the highway, possibly resulting in property damage, personal
                injury, or death.
            </para>
            <para>
                <title>MODELS INVOLVED</title>
            </para>
            <para>This Safety Recall involves 4800 4x4 models with a Fabco TC-200 transfer case (feature code 13TJZ
                ONLY) built 6/30/1999 through 5/8/2002.
            </para>
        </defect>
        <ownernote>
            <para>International Truck and Engine Corporation will notify owners of this campaign on their vehicles.
                During the recall process a listing of owner names and addresses will be furnished to the involved
                dealers to enable dealers to follow up with owners and have the vehicles corrected. You must limit the
                use of this listing to this campaign because the list may contain information obtained from state motor
                vehicle registration records and the use of such motor vehicle registration data for purposes other than
                this campaign is a violation of law in several states.
            </para>
        </ownernote>
        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="13">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent serious eye injury, always wear safe eye protection when you perform vehicle
                        maintenance or service.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent unexpected movement of the vehicle and possible serious personal injury or death,
                        block the wheels to prevent the vehicle from moving in both directions.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <title>FRONT DRIVESHAFT INSPECTION</title>
            </para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">DO NOT</emph>
                perform the FRONT DRIVESHAFT REPLACEMENT if a vehicle was modified in ANY way from factory original.
                Examples of modification can be as follows:
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Transfer Case re-positioned by Truck Equipment Manufacturer (TEM) due to specialized truck
                        body installation.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Center bearing installed. The suspect vehicles were originally built with one (1) front drive
                        shaft. If there are two (2) FRONT drive shafts,
                        <emph type="bold">DO NOT</emph>
                        perform the FRONT DRIVESHAFT REPLACEMENT.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>NEW SHAFT DATE CODE INSPECTION</title>
            </para>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Locate label and date code on new drive shaft.</para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <figure id="f0550112" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550112.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Date Code Location</caption>
            </figure>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>Date code format is as follows: DAY.MONTH.YEAR. The example above corresponds to October, 6th,
                        2005.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>If date code is between
                        <emph type="bold">01.06.04</emph>
                        and
                        <emph type="bold">11.10.04</emph>
                        (June 1st, 2004 thru October 11th 2004), perform the following inspection on the shaft's
                        companion flanges.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>If the date code is after 11.10.04, continue on to
                        <emph type="bold">FRONT DRIVESHAFT REPLACEMENT</emph>.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Inspect the serrations in BOTH flanges for excess material in the FLAT AREA BETWEEN THE
                        SERRATIONS.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <figure id="f0550113" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550113.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Flange Serrations</caption>
            </figure>
            <randlist type="bullet">
                <item>
                    <para>If a burr, or excess material is found, use a die grinder to remove it.</para>
                    <randlist type="dash">
                        <item>
                            <para>
                                <emph type="boldital">DO NOT REMOVE SERRATION MATERIAL.</emph>
                            </para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Use the mating companion flange (transfer case and front axle) as the gauge to check
                                that there is full engagement of the serration or if interference continues to be
                                present.
                            </para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>Refer to Step 1 below. Dry fit should indicate full engagement of flange serrations.
                            </para>
                        </item>
                    </randlist>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>If no burr or excess material is found, ensure dry fit during Step 1 indicates full engagement
                        of flange serrations. Continue to
                        <emph type="bold">FRONT DRIVESHAFT REPLACEMENT.</emph>
                    </para>
                </item>
            </randlist>
            <para>
                <title>FRONT DRIVESHAFT REPLACEMENT</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dry fit and lay out the new shaft and flanges to determine which side belongs on the
                    axle side and which belongs on the transfer case side. Mark flange and shaft for ease in
                    installation and proper alignment.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550101" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550101.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1 - Front Axle Side - Small Spline</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Front axle flange has SMALL diameter splines. Transfer case flange has LARGE diameter
                        splines.
                    </callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove original FRONT driveshaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove front axle yoke and shaft seal. Save the washers, they will be re-used during
                    flange installation.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f055010" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550102.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove transfer case yoke and shaft seal. You will need to engage the transfer case to
                    prevent the front output shaft from rotating.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550103" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550103.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new front axle input shaft seal.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550104" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550104.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new front axle flange, washer and nut. Torque nut to 420-450 Lbf-Ft (570-610
                    Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new transfer case output shaft seal.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550105" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550105.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new transfer case flange, washer and nut. Torque nut to 460-500 Lbf-Ft (625-678
                    Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>You will need to use a thin wall socket to properly tighten the nut.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0550106" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550106.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 6</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disengage the transfer case so the output shaft is free to rotate.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new driveshaft starting with the front axle.
                    <emph type="bold">INSTALL SHAFT WITH SLIP JOINT TOWARDS THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE.</emph>
                    Align mark on flange with mark on shaft. Install and torque bolts to 88-92 Lbf-Ft (120-125 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate transfer case output shaft until the mark on transfer case flange aligns with
                    mark on shaft. Install and torque bolts to 88-92 Lbf-Ft (120-125 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550107" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550107.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check and fill, if necessary, front axle and transfer case oil level.</para>
            </step1>
            <para>
                <title>AIR DRYER ROTATION</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Some vehicles built with feature code 804EMZ, air dryer relocation, will require the air
                    dryer to be rotated and re-mounted.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the vehicle's air dryer has an output elbow in close proximity (less than 1"
                    [25.4mm]) to the drive shaft (see Figure 8), a rotation is required. Continue to step 16.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550108" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550108.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the air dryer elbow is not located in close proximity (greater than 1" [25.4mm]) to
                    the driveshaft, then the service procedure is completed.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the air dryer mounting bolts. Loosen upper air dryer strap bolts.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0550109" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550109.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Air dryer strap bolts</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Air dryer mounting bolts</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate air dryer and re-install mounting bolts; tighten strap bolts.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Please only rotate one (1) mounting bolt position.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0550110" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550110.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 10 - Rotated Air Dryer</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Rotate air dryer clockwise to this position.</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0550111" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../recallfigures/g0550111.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         scalefitheight="296px"/>
                <caption>Figure 11 - Rotated Air Dryer</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
